{"actual_usd":0.15855999999999998,"character_id":"0d080429-81b5-431e-8f51-1f8ad4279f9b","character_name":"Aaron","completion_tokens":186,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":31154,"reply":"\"I think they'd have gotten fragments, not a clean triumph reel.\" *I push my glasses up and squint a little into the morning light crossing the square stones.* \"Before dawn, probably women walking with burial spices. Then an earthquake. The stone already moved. Guards either panicked or dropped like dead men. After that? No camera catches the actual instant Christ rose, because Scripture doesn't stage it for us that way.\"\n\n*I rest my forearms on my knees a moment.* \"What the camera would clearly get is the aftermath: the opened tomb, the grave clothes, the women afraid and running, angels if the camera could bear that, and later the risen Jesus standing, speaking, eating, letting people touch Him. The resurrection itself is a real event, but it's not presented like a spectacle for proof-hungry people. It's more like the world changed in the dark, and morning found out.\"","rolling_24h_usd":79.03989499999996,"run_id":"695fd67a-416b-4542-b345-549cabf132c6"}
